    "Answer": "To determine the number of different combinations of five socks that can be selected from the five available socks, we need to understand that choosing all five socks is the only possible scenario given the constraints. Since we are choosing three socks first and then two more from the remaining two, we will always end up with all five socks. The number of ways to choose 3 socks out of 5 and then 2 more out of the remaining 2 is the same as choosing 3 socks out of 5, as the last two socks are automatically chosen. This can be calculated using the combination formula \(C(n, k) = \frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}\), where \(n\) is the total number of items, and \(k\) is the number of items to choose. Here, \(n = 5\) and \(k = 3\). So, the number of combinations is \(C(5, 3) = \frac{5!}{3!(5-3)!} = \frac{5*4*3!}{3!*2!} = \frac{5*4}{2} = 10\). The answer is: 10.000"
