```python
{
    "question": "A set of $n$ students participate in a math club. Each student can be part of any number of $5$-student study groups, but no two study groups can have the exact same $5$ members. The club's records show an interesting statistic: The average, over all subsets of size $9$ of the set of $n$ students, of the number of complete study groups whose members are among those $9$ students is equal to the reciprocal of the average, over all subsets of size $8$ of the set of $n$ students, of the number of complete study groups whose members are among those $8$ students. How many values of $n$, $9 \leq n \leq 2017$, can be the number of students in the club?",
    "solution": "Let's denote the number of $5$-student study groups as $G$. For any subset of $9$ students, the number of $5$-student study groups that can be formed from these $9$ students is $\binom{9}{5} = 126$. The average number of these $5$-student study groups for all subsets of size $9$ is then $126G / \binom{n}{9}$. Similarly, for any subset of $8$ students, the number of $5$-student study groups that can be formed is $\binom{8}{5} = 56$. The average number of these $5$-student study groups for all subsets of size $8$ is then $56G / \binom{n}{8}$. According to the problem, the average for $9$-subsets is the reciprocal of the average for $8$-subsets: \[ \frac{126G}{\binom{n}{9}} = \frac{\binom{n}{8}}{56G} \] Simplifying, we get: \[ 126G \cdot 56G = \binom{n}{9} \cdot \binom{n}{8} \] \[ 7056G^2 = \frac{n!}{9!(n-9)!} \cdot \frac{n!}{8!(n-8)!} \] \[ 7056G^2 = \frac{n!}{9!(n-9)!} \cdot \frac{n \cdot (n-1) \cdot (n-2) \cdot (n-3) \cdot (n-4) \cdot (n-5) \cdot (n-6) \cdot (n-7) \cdot (n-8)!}{8!(n-8)!} \] \[ 7056G^2 = \frac{n! \cdot n \cdot (n-1) \cdot (n-2) \cdot (n-3) \cdot (n-4) \cdot (n-5) \cdot (n-6) \cdot (n-7)}{9! \cdot 8! \cdot 9!} \] \[ 7056G^2 = \frac{n \cdot (n-1) \cdot (n-2) \cdot (n-3) \cdot (n-4) \cdot (n-5) \cdot (n-6) \cdot (n-7) \cdot n!}{9! \cdot 8! \cdot 9!} \] \[ 7056G^2 = \frac{n \cdot (n-1) \cdot (n-2) \cdot (n-3) \cdot (n-4) \cdot (n-5) \cdot (n-6) \cdot (n-7) \cdot n \cdot (n-1) \cdot (n-2) \cdot (n-3) \cdot (n-4) \cdot (n-5) \cdot (n-6) \cdot (n-7) \cdot (n-8)!}{9! \cdot 8! \cdot 9! \cdot 8!} \] \[ 7056G^2 = \frac{n^2 \cdot (n-1)^2 \cdot (n-2)^2 \cdot (n-3)^2 \cdot (n-4)^2 \cdot (n-5)^2 \cdot (n-6)^2 \cdot (n-7)^2 \cdot (n-8)!}{(9!)^2 \cdot (8!)^2} \] \[ 7056G^2 = \frac{n^2 \cdot (n-1)^2 \cdot (n-2)^2 \cdot (n-3)^2 \cdot (n-4)^2 \cdot (n-5)^2 \cdot (n-6)^2 \cdot (n-7)^2}{(9!)^2} \] The only way for this equation to hold true for integer values of $n$ is if $n$ is such that the equation simplifies to a form that allows $G$ to be an integer. This occurs when $n = 12$. We need to check the range $9 \leq n \leq 2017$ for values of $n$ that satisfy this condition. The only value that works is $n = 12$. Therefore, there is only one value of $n$ in the given range that satisfies the condition. The answer is: 1"
}
